Question 3
What are Web Components? How is LWC based on Web Component standards?
Companies that asked this: Salesforce, Microsoft, Amazon, Cognizant, Genpact

Answer:
Web Components are a set of web platform APIs that allow you to create reusable custom HTML elements. They consist of four main technologies:

1. Custom Elements - Define new HTML tags

2. Shadow DOM - Encapsulated DOM and styling

3. HTML Templates - Reusable markup templates

4. ES Modules - Standard way to import/export JavaScript


LWC is built on these standards, which means:

Native Performance: No framework overhead, runs directly in the browser

Future-proof: Based on web standards, not proprietary technology

Interoperability: Can work with other web components and frameworks

Developer Familiarity: Uses standard HTML, CSS, and JavaScript


Example:

Traditional Web Component:

class HelloElement extends HTMLElement {
    connectedCallback() {
        this.innerHTML = '<p>Hello, World!</p>';
    }
}
customElements.define('hello-element', HelloElement);

LWC Equivalent:
import { LightningElement } from 'lwc';
 
export default class HelloWorld extends LightningElement {
    connectedCallback() {
        console.log('Component connected to DOM');
    }
}
<template>
    <p>Hello, World!</p>
</template>


How LWC Uses Web Standards:

Custom Elements: LWC components become custom HTML elements

<c-my-component></c-my-component>
Shadow DOM: Provides style and DOM encapsulation.  Styles in component css file  only affect this component

Templates: HTML templates with data binding

<template>
    <p>{greeting}</p>
</template>
ES Modules: Standard import/export syntax

import { LightningElement, api } from 'lwc';
export default class MyComponent extends LightningElement {}

Interview Tips:

Emphasize that LWC follows web standards, not proprietary frameworks

Mention browser compatibility and performance benefits

Explain that developers can leverage existing web development skills

Note that this makes LWC future-proof
